<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-15</title>

<p>This week's strongest signal is that embodied AI is being rebuilt as a <b>full-stack systems problem</b> rather than a model-architecture problem. The most interesting papers do not introduce a single new loss or backbone; they argue that the gap between foundation-model capability and real robot deployment is now in the integration layer — how to keep visual priors alive while adapting to embodiment, how to turn unstructured human video into grounded dexterous policies, and how to give an agent a persistent, verifiable memory and skill runtime. Three threads stood out: <b>Xiaomi-Robotics-U0</b> reframes embodied generation as a continuation of foundation image/video generation; <b>EgoSteer</b> closes the data-engineering and deployment loop for dual-hand dexterous VLAs; and <b>ABot-AgentOS</b> proposes a deliberative agent operating system with lifelong multi-modal memory. Each is ambitious, each has a different artifact footprint, and together they map where the field is putting its effort now.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> EgoSteer is the clearest seed for a buildable research thread because it ships the full stack — data pipeline, robot stack, training code, and model weights — and backs its claims with internal but well-documented real-robot scaling curves. Xiaomi-Robotics-U0 is the most eye-catching unification bet, but its boldest claims rest on a video checkpoint that is not yet public. ABot-AgentOS is a thoughtful architecture paper whose strongest contribution is a typed memory graph, though its full system artifacts are still missing.</p>
</callout>

<h1>World models as embodied synthesis engines</h1>

<p>The dominant question in this theme is whether an embodied world model should be a narrow post-training fork from a foundation generator, or a broader continuation that keeps text-to-image, editing, and robot-centric generation in the same model. Xiaomi-Robotics-U0 takes the second path at serious scale.</p>

