<hr/>

<h2>Xiaomi-Robotics-U0: Unified Embodied Synthesis with World Foundation Model</h2>

<p>Xiaomi Robotics (arXiv 2607.11643) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.11643">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.11643">PDF</a> · <a href="https://robotics.xiaomi.com/xiaomi-robotics-u0.html">project</a></p>

<p>The paper's central question is whether embodied generation can be a <b>natural extension</b> of foundation image and video generation, rather than a specialized fork that forgets general visual priors. Xiaomi-Robotics-U0 is a 38-billion-parameter dense autoregressive model that jointly trains on text-to-image, any-to-image editing, embodied scene generation, embodied transfer, and embodied video generation. The bet is that co-training with internet-scale visual tasks preserves semantics and controllability while robot data supplies multi-view consistency and embodiment constraints.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:xiaomi-robotics-u0:capabilities]]</p>

<p><b>Architecture and training.</b> The released config is a 64-layer decoder with hidden size 5120, 64 heads, 8 GQA KV heads, intermediate size 25600, and a vocab of 282926 tokens — roughly 34B dense parameters, close to the paper's "38B" claim. It inherits Emu3.5's IBQ visual tokenizer (16×16 spatial compression) and extends the text vocabulary with the image codebook, so all modalities live in a single discrete token space. Training is staged: <b>single-step co-training</b> on T2I, X2I, embodied scene generation, and embodied transfer; then <b>sequential training</b> on image-text-interleaved subtask-subgoal sequences and multi-FPS manipulation videos (1, 3, and 5 FPS). Everything reduces to next-token prediction.</p>

<p>The structured control formulation is one of the most concrete ideas. Embodied transfer conditions on multi-view inverse-depth maps and a scene description disentangled into five independent dimensions: workspace, task objects, irrelevant objects, lighting, and background. Inspecting the released task configs confirms these five dimensions are exactly the fields used in the system prompts, and depth preprocessing uses Depth Anything 3. This is the mechanism that lets the model perform style-aware, geometrically consistent data augmentation for downstream policies.</p>

<p><b>FlashAR+ acceleration.</b> High-resolution autoregressive image generation is slow in raster order. Xiaomi adds a FlashAR-derived extension: a vertical prediction branch, horizontal and vertical prediction heads, a learnable fusion gate, and an anti-diagonal decoding schedule. Position (r,c) is generated at step r+c, so a 32×32 token grid drops from 1024 serial steps to 63. A small probe of the anti-diagonal schedule gives the speed-up structure:</p>

<pre lang="text" caption="FlashAR anti-diagonal decoding (32×32 grid)"><code>Raster AR serial steps: 1024
FlashAR anti-diagonal serial steps: 63
Theoretical speed-up: 16.25x

step 0: [(0, 0)]
step 1: [(0, 1), (1, 0)]
step 2: [(0, 2), (1, 1), (2, 0)]
...
step 62: [(31, 31)]</code></pre>

<p>The released loss in the FlashAR model file is <code>loss = loss_fuse + 0.05 * loss_h + 0.05 * loss_v + 0.2 * loss_distill</code>, matching the paper's Equation (5). Combined with a vLLM patch for diagonal scheduling and paged KV-cache, the paper reports 5.44 s/image at 1024×1024 on one H20, or 82.9× faster than AR eager.</p>

<p><b>What the external signals confirm and what they don't.</b> The good news: the model weights, inference code for four engine modes (AR eager, AR+vLLM, FlashAR eager, FlashAR+vLLM), and composable task configs are public on HuggingFace and GitHub. The code confirms the unified token space, the five structured scene dimensions, the FlashAR mechanism, and the depth-conditioned transfer pipeline. The cautious news: the <b>video checkpoint is listed as "coming soon."</b> That means the sequential-world-modeling claims, the World Arena ranking, and the real-world policy augmentation experiments — including the highlighted π₀.₅ jump from 36.9% to 63.2% OOD success — cannot be independently reproduced yet. Training recipes, data mixtures, and the VLM annotation pipeline are also not released, and the comparison against GPT-Image-2.0 uses a small internal benchmark (300 transfer samples, 400 scene-generation samples).</p>

<p><b>Takeaway.</b> Xiaomi-Robotics-U0 is a credible unification attempt with real released weights for single-step embodied generation and a well-engineered acceleration path. The idea of treating embodied synthesis as a continuation of foundation generation is intellectually clean. But the paper's boldest claim — that the same model unifies long-horizon embodied video generation and serves as a scalable data engine — currently rests on a video checkpoint and training pipeline that are not public. Treat the single-step results and FlashAR speed-up as substantiated; treat the sequential/video story as promising-yet-unverified.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Dexterous manipulation from egocentric priors</h1>

<p>High-DoF dual-hand manipulation has been data-starved and task-specific. EgoSteer argues that the bottleneck is not architecture alone but the full stack: curating egocentric video into usable pre-training data, grounding human-hand priors on a real robot with modest teleoperation, and designing a VLA training objective that can use both.</p>

