<h2>EgoSteer: A Full-Stack System Towards Steerable Dexterous Manipulation from Egocentric Videos</h2>

<p>Zhong et al. (arXiv 2607.09701) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.09701">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.09701">PDF</a> · <a href="https://egosteer.github.io/">project</a></p>

<p>EgoSteer asks whether a single dual-dexterous-hand VLA can follow free-form language across 40+ real-world tasks by pre-training on large-scale egocentric human video and grounding with only modest real-robot teleoperation. The authors' answer is less a new algorithm than a full-stack integration: a data pipeline called <b>EgoSmith</b>, a unified robot stack with human-in-the-loop correction, and a world-model-enhanced flow VLA.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:egosteer:overview]]</p>

<p><b>EgoSmith.</b> The pipeline curates 12 raw egocentric datasets into a 9.6K-hour pre-training corpus. It pre-filters locomotion and occluded hands with optical-flow and YOLO gates; reconstructs metric world-space hand trajectories using HaWoR's ViT but replaces DROID-SLAM with faster DPVO odometry and anchors it to metric depth from Any4D; labels clips with five-level language instructions from Qwen3.5-VL-Plus; and post-filters at episode, chunk, and frame levels. The authors report roughly 9× throughput over HaWoR and improved accuracy, though world-space hand joint error is still ~86 mm on the strictest metric, so the pre-training labels are approximate.</p>

<p><b>Robot stack and DAgger.</b> The hardware is a RealMan platform with two 7-DoF arms and two 6-DoF Ruiyan RY-H2 hands, teleoperated at 100/80 Hz using PsiBot gloves and Vive trackers. The key deployment idea is <b>relative motion mapping</b>: when an operator intervenes, the system records robot and human poses at takeover and applies the operator's relative motion to the robot's current state, avoiding handover jumps. Only intervention segments are kept for DAgger training. The collected real-robot dataset is 187 hours / 55K trajectories across 193 tasks.</p>

<p><b>EgoSteer model.</b> A Qwen3-VL-2B VLM backbone is paired with two lightweight transformer experts. Inputs are a language instruction, camera intrinsics, 6 image frames at 1 FPS, 6 states, and a 32-step action target. The unified 48-D action space is bimanual wrist poses + fingertip keypoints (rot6d for wrist, coordinate displacements for fingers). A 14-layer DiT-style action expert (hidden 1024, intermediate 2816, ~300M params) uses joint attention to the backbone KV cache and conditional flow matching for training. A second 4-layer world-model expert (~70M params) predicts frozen DINOv3-ViT-L/16 features of the future frame 1 s ahead and is discarded at inference. Training-time RTC (Real-Time Chunking) reserves a random prefix of the action chunk so the model learns to denoise the suffix while the robot executes the prefix, eliminating inference pauses. The config probe confirms the architectural numbers exactly:</p>

<pre lang="json" caption="Architectural hyperparameters from official Hydra configs"><code>{
  "unified_action_space": {
    "state_dim": 48,
    "action_dim": 48,
    "state_history_frames": 6,
    "action_horizon": 32
  },
  "action_expert": {
    "hidden_size": 1024,
    "intermediate_size": 2816,
    "num_layers": 14,
    "num_heads": 8,
    "use_adaln": true
  },
  "world_model": {
    "frozen_teacher": "facebook/dinov3-vitl16-pretrain-lvd1689m",
    "num_expert_layers": 4,
    "expert_hidden_size": 1024,
    "expert_intermediate_size": 4096
  },
  "losses": {
    "ce_loss_weight": 0.05,
    "flow_loss_weight": 1.0,
    "wm_loss_weight": 1.0
  }
}</code></pre>

<p><b>Results.</b> After pre-training on 9.6K hours, post-training on 187 hours, and 3 DAgger iterations, EgoSteer reports 75% average success on 32 seen tasks, 65% on 4 compositional tasks, and 62% on 4 unseen tasks. The scaling curve is the strongest scientific signal: from-scratch fails on harder tasks, while 3K / 6K / 9.6K hours yield 40% / 43% / 60% on a 10-task subset. DAgger is also efficient: on 4 failure-prone tasks, success rises from 22.5% to 62.5% after only 8.3 hours of corrections. Ablations show that removing the world-model objective, training-time RTC, or EgoSmith filtering each drops performance substantially.</p>

