<h2>ABot-AgentOS: A General Robotic Agent OS with Lifelong Multi-modal Memory</h2>

<p>AMAP CV Lab (arXiv 2607.10350) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2607.10350">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.10350">PDF</a></p>

<p>ABot-AgentOS argues that recent VLMs and VLAs give robots perception and action prediction, but the missing layer is a general runtime for reasoning, memory, tool use, verification, and cross-embodiment execution. The paper proposes an <b>Agent OS</b> that sits above low-level controllers and below foundation models, with three public-facing contributions: a modular agent harness, a new executable benchmark (EmbodiedWorldBench), and a typed multi-modal memory graph with failure-driven self-evolution.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:abot-agentos:architecture]]</p>

<p><b>Agent Harness.</b> The runtime uses an edge-cloud LLM router: a lightweight Tiny LLM handles every turn, escalating to a cloud Large LLM on demand. The Agent Harness separates three roles often entangled in a single controller: a <b>Main LLM</b> for scene-conditioned semantic planning, a <b>Skill Runner</b> subagent that absorbs procedural detail in an isolated local context, and a <b>Verifier</b> that supervises execution at runtime, skill-level, and finish-time. This is a sensible response to the reasoning-execution gap: embodied tasks rarely emit explicit success signals, so the agent must cross-check language-level belief against trajectory evidence.</p>

<p><b>Multi-modal graph memory.</b> The strongest concrete contribution is the memory system. Long-term experience is stored as a typed graph <latex>\mathcal{G}=(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E})</latex> with nodes for sources, evidence, entities, places, sessions, and semantic events, and edges for temporal order, containment, observation, participation, location, identity continuity, spatial relations, and provenance. Each node carries a compact JSON-style record with time reference, evidence summary, confidence, and provenance, so answers can be traced back to source observations rather than relying on parametric memory.</p>

<p>Retrieval uses a hybrid seed-selection score:</p>

<p><latex>s(q,v) = \lambda_{\mathrm{sem}} s_{\mathrm{sem}}(q,v) + \lambda_{\mathrm{lex}} s_{\mathrm{lex}}(q,v) + \lambda_{\mathrm{meta}} s_{\mathrm{meta}}(q,v) + \lambda_{\mathrm{type}} s_{\mathrm{type}}(q,v)</latex></p>

<p>Top seeds are expanded along typed edges into a local evidence subgraph, and each run records a retrieval trace. This traceability is what enables the failure-driven self-evolution loop: after each evaluation split, diagnosed memory failures are compiled into gated runtime "evo-assets" that can only be promoted to later splits, preventing ground-truth leakage while enabling cumulative improvement.</p>

<p><b>What the probe shows.</b> Because the full system is not released, I built a small runnable reconstruction of the graph memory, retriever, and evidence-subgraph expansion. It writes the paper's "I adopted a Maltese dog yesterday" example into typed nodes and edges and answers queries from the resulting evidence subgraph. For the query "Where is the dog now?" the retriever correctly follows temporal and location edges to the latest observation:</p>

<pre lang="json" caption="ABot-AgentOS memory-graph probe: evidence subgraph for "Where is the dog now?""><code>{
  "query": "Where is the dog now?",
  "seed_nodes": [
    "event:home-002:2026-07-15T08:00:00Z",
    "place:living_room",
    "place:backyard"
  ],
  "retrieved_node_ids": [
    "evidence:frames/home-002/000020.jpg",
    "place:backyard",
    "event:home-002:2026-07-15T08:00:00Z",
    "entity:Maltese_dog:home-002"
  ],
  "retrieved_edges": [
    ["event:home-002", "location", "place:backyard"],
    ["event:home-002", "provenance", "evidence:frames/home-002/000020.jpg"],
    ["event:home-002", "observation", "entity:Maltese_dog:home-002"],
    ["entity:Maltese_dog:home-002", "location", "place:backyard"]
  ]
}</code></pre>

<p><b>Results and artifact status.</b> On an initial EmbodiedWorldBench subset, ABot-AgentOS improves over a ReAct baseline by +11.99 TSR and +10.84 GCR with the same backbone, and swapping to a stronger main LLM adds another +6.22 TSR. The memory evaluation is more substantial: 87.5 on LoCoMo (near human 87.9), 59.9 on OpenEQA EM-EQA, 88.6 on Mem-Gallery, 76.5 Acc@All on NExT-QA, and 65.4 on EgoLifeQA. Self-evolution adds modest but consistent gains, especially +4.1 on NExT-QA where temporal/relation edges matter.</p>

<p>However, the public artifact situation is thin. The GitHub repo is a placeholder, the project page linked from arXiv returns 404, and EmbodiedWorldBench is described as future work. The strongest controlled comparison is Static vs. +Self-evo under the same implementation; the agent subset results should be read as preliminary.</p>

<p><b>Takeaway.</b> ABot-AgentOS is best understood as a well-integrated system-architecture paper. Its most persuasive contribution is the typed memory graph and the retrieval-trace design, which post competitive numbers across five memory benchmarks. The Agent Harness is sensible but the agent results are on an unreleased subset of an unreleased benchmark. The report should flag the artifact gap honestly: the community cannot yet build on the full system, but the memory mechanism itself is concrete and implementable.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p>Three patterns cut across this week's papers.</p>

<p><b>1. Full-stack integration is the new differentiator.</b> EgoSteer does not win on a single architectural novelty; it wins by releasing the data pipeline, robot stack, training code, and weights together. Xiaomi-Robotics-U0's most impressive number is a systems number (82.9× speed-up via FlashAR+vLLM). ABot-AgentOS's value proposition is an integrated runtime layer. The field is moving past "better backbone" toward "better glue."</p>

<p><b>2. Artifact footprint predicts how much to believe.</b> EgoSteer shipped nearly everything, so its claims are the most auditable. Xiaomi-Robotics-U0 shipped the single-step weights and inference code but held back the video checkpoint and training pipeline, so its sequential claims are provisional. ABot-AgentOS shipped a detailed architecture and memory results but almost no system code, so its agent-benchmark claims are preliminary. The honest report should scale confidence with artifact availability.</p>

<p><b>3. World models are being asked to do two jobs at once.</b> Both Xiaomi-Robotics-U0 and EgoSteer use world-model-like objectives, but for different purposes: Xiaomi wants a generative data engine that can roll out synthetic embodied trajectories; EgoSteer wants a future-state prediction auxiliary loss that improves representation learning in a VLA. The first is generative and deployment-expensive; the second is discriminative and training-only. Both are legitimate, but they should not be conflated.</p>

<p><b>What to watch next.</b> Whether Xiaomi releases its video checkpoint and whether the World Arena results hold up under independent submission. Whether EgoSteer's open-sourced Base checkpoint enables transfer to other dexterous platforms beyond RealMan. Whether ABot-AgentOS follows through with code and EmbodiedWorldBench. And whether any of these systems add tactile or force feedback, which remains the obvious missing modality for contact-rich dexterity.</p>
